{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a194070d-de33-4078-be79-e132865e90ea","content":"The project directory doesn't exist yet in this workspace, but I can tell you exactly what to configure. To publish a C# MCP server (stdio transport) as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org, add these properties to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName> <!-- CLI command name -->\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server tool.</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — marks the project as a dotnet tool.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the command users will run (e.g., `dotnet tool run my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType=Exe`** — required for tools.\n\n**To pack & publish:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet pack -c Release\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_NUGET_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Users install with:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```\n\nSince your MCP server uses **stdio transport**, it works naturally as a dotnet tool — the host launches the command and communicates over stdin/stdout. No extra transport configuration needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"19772727-69f7-4d10-b2f3-913304ab875b","outputTokens":471,"requestId":"AC02:1F8B8F:E2A9C4:118F029:6A012DA9"},"id":"21ddfe05-21fa-450d-9948-7831f9dfc26d","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:15:32.091Z","parentId":"a2ab43a7-d306-4318-9edb-0d7b400882f1"}
